===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|clappen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|clæppan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*klappōną}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|klappen}}, {{cog|is|klappa}}, and {{cog|fo|klappa}}. {{doublet|en|clepe|yclept}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
[[File:Steve Reich.jpg|thumb|right|Two men clapping.]]

# The act of [[strike|striking]] the palms of the hands, or any two surfaces, together.
#: {{ux|en|He summoned the waiter with a '''clap'''.}}
# The explosive sound of [[thunder]].
#* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|chapter=[Episode 12: The Cyclops]|passage=The deafening '''claps''' of thunder and the dazzling flashes of lightning which lit up the ghastly scene testified that the artillery of heaven had lent its supernatural pomp to the already gruesome spectacle.}}
# Any loud, sudden, explosive [[sound]] made by striking hard surfaces together, or resembling such a sound.
#: {{ux|en|Off in the distance, he heard the '''clap''' of thunder.}}
#* {{RQ:Swift Directions to Servants}}
#*: Give the door such a '''clap''', as you go out, as will shake the whole room.
# A [[slap]] with the hand, usually in a [[jovial]] manner.
#: {{ux|en|His father's affection never went further than a handshake or a '''clap''' on the shoulder.}}
# A single, sudden act or motion; a stroke; a blow.
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare King Lear|I|iv|passage=What, fifty of my followers at a '''clap'''!}}
#* {{RQ:Stevenson Kidnapped|passage=But it took him a long time to get down-stairs, and a still longer to undo the fastenings, repenting (I dare say) and taken with fresh '''claps''' of fear at every second step and every bolt and bar.}}
# {{lb|en|falconry}} The [[nether]] part of the [[beak]] of a [[hawk]].
# {{lb|en|Yorkshire}} A dropping of [[cow]] [[dung]] (presumably from the sound made as it hits the ground) <ref>Edward Peacock, ''A Glossary of Words Used in the Wapentakes of Manley and Corringham, Lincolnshire'', [http://books.google.com/books?id=c3oKAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA188&dq=clap&as_brr=1 p 188]</ref>
#* '''1890''', John Nicholson, ''Folk Lore of East Yorkshire'', [http://books.google.com/books?id=tw0naTcLHeMC&pg=PA139&dq=clap&as_brr=1&ei=pGvbRtu_E4SipgL0peiSCw page 139]
#*: “Oh! get some coo '''clap''' (cow dung), mix it wi’ fish oil (whale oil), put it on, and let it stop on all neet.”

