====Verb====
{{en-verb|past2=clapt|past2_qual=archaic}}
{{wikipedia|Clapping}}

# To [[strike]] the palms of the hands together, creating a sharp sound.
#: {{ux|en|The children began to '''clap''' in time with the music.}}
# To [[applaud]].
#: {{ux|en|The audience loudly '''clapped''' the actress, who responded with a deep curtsey.}}
#: {{ux|en|It isn’t the singers they are '''clapping'''; it's the composer.}}
# To slap with the hand in a [[jovial]] manner.
#: {{ux|en|He would often '''clap''' his teammates on the back for encouragement.}}
# To bring two [[surface]]s together forcefully, creating a sharp sound.
#: {{ux|en|He '''clapped''' the empty glass down on the table.}}
#: {{ux|en|She '''clapped''' the book shut.}}
#: {{ux|en|He '''clapped''' across the floor in his boots.}}
#* '''1681''', {{w|Andrew Marvell}}, ''{{w|The Garden (poem)|The Garden}}''
#*: Then like a bird it sits and sings, / Then whets and '''claps''' its silver wings.
#* {{RQ:Smollett Peregrine Pickle|chapter=He is Concerned in a Dangerous Adventure with a Certain Gardener;{{nb...|Sublimes His Ideas, Commences Gallant, and Becomes Acquainted with Miss Emily Gauntlet.}}|page=49|column=1|passage=[...] Pipes, who acted as the enemy's forlorn hope, advanced to the gate with great intrepidity, and '''clapping''' his foot to the door, which was none of the ſtouteſt, with the execution and diſpatch of a petard, ſplit it into a thouſand pieces.}}
## {{lb|en|slang}} To have [[sex]].
##: {{ux|en|'''clap''' alien cheeks}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[slam]] (a door or window); formerly often construed with {{m|en|to}}.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-1|II|5|pasage=Hostesse '''clap''' to the doores.}}
#* {{RQ:Dryden All For Love}}
#*: The doors around me '''clapped'''.
#*'''1792''', {{w|Thomas Holcroft}}, ''Anna St. Ives'', vol. VII, letter 119:
#*:Her fear gave her strength; she threw Laura away, and '''clapped''' to the door.
# To create or assemble (something) [[hastily]] (usually followed by ''up'' or ''together'').
#: {{ux|en|We should '''clap''' together a shelter before nightfall.}}
#: {{ux|en|The rival factions '''clapped''' up a truce.}}
# To set or put, usually in haste.
#: {{ux|en|The sheriff '''clapped''' him in jail.}}
#: {{ux|en|She was the prettiest thing I'd ever '''clapped''' eyes on.}}
#* {{RQ:Locke Education|138}}
#*: He had just time to get in and '''clap''' to the door.
#* {{RQ:Lamb Essays of Elia|passage='''Clap''' an extinguisher upon your irony.}}
# {{lb|en|slang|AAVE}} To [[shoot]] (somebody) with a gun.

